(90, 'SS7 Attack', 'SS7 Hacking: The Invisible Threat to Mobile Security\r\n\r\nSS7 (Signaling System No. 7) is the 50-year-old backbone of global telecom networks, controlling call routing, SMS, and mobile data. Designed for reliability—not security—it lacks encryption and authentication, making it a goldmine for hackers.\r\n\r\nWhy SS7 is Dangerous:\r\n\r\nCall Interception: Attackers silently redirect calls to eavesdrop or impersonate victims.\r\n\r\nSMS Hijacking: Steal 2FA codes, bank alerts, or private messages.\r\n\r\nLocation Tracking: Pinpoint a phone’s real-time GPS coordinates.\r\n\r\nFraud: Clone numbers, bypass toll gates, or charge premium services to victims.\r\n\r\nHow It Works:\r\nHackers exploit SS7 by sending malicious signaling packets—often using cheap telecom gear or compromised carrier access. No physical access to the target’s device is needed.\r\n\r\nWho’s At Risk?\r\n\r\nBusinesses: CEO fraud, corporate espionage.\r\n\r\nJournalists/Activists: Surveillance risks.\r\n\r\nEveryone: 2FA bypass affects all mobile users.\r\n\r\nCourse Focus:\r\nThis hands-on training teaches:\r\n\r\nSS7’s technical flaws\r\n\r\nReal-world attack simulations (interception, tracking)\r\n\r\nDefense strategies for individuals & enterprises\r\n\r\nWhy Learn SS7 Hacking?\r\n\r\nPentesters: Uncover critical telecom vulnerabilities.\r\n\r\nSecurity Teams: Defend against invisible threats.\r\n\r\nEthical Hackers: Master a high-impact attack vector.', 'SS7 Hacks Made Simple: Break calls, steal SMS & track phones and Many More. Master telecom hacking.', 5, 13, 1499.00, NULL, 1, 1, 'Advanced', 1, '../uploads/thumbnails/1743080660_6867f585_fe50_4fc2_bd10_42147e6e1953.png', NULL, '2025-03-27 13:04:20', '2025-03-27 13:04:57', '', 0);

